ce:section.ce:para:
Buffer solution plays an important role in the selectivity of Fe3+. Hg2+ was chosen as the contrast ion to study the effect of buffer solution due to its quenching effect on NCDs. The quenching efficiencies (QE) of Fe3+ and Hg2+ on NCDs in different buffer solutions are shown in Fig. 10
                           . It is found that in DI water system, the QE of Fe3+ is lower than that of Hg2+, while in tris-HCl, the QE of Fe3+ is much higher than that of Hg2+, indicating that the selectivity of NCDs to Fe3+ is enhanced. By comparing photographs of NCDs-Mn+ mixed solutions presence and absence of tris-HCl buffer (
                              Fig. S14
                           ), it can be seen that the color of the solution with Fe3+ is obviously darker after adding tris-HCl, displaying that the degree of hydrolysis of Fe3+ was enhanced and colloids were formed. To further study the effect of buffer solutions, NaAc-HAc and NaH2PO4-Na2HPO4 buffers were used to evaluate the QEs. As shown in Fig. 10, consistent with the water system, Fe3+ also showed a lower QE than that of Hg2+in these two systems, implying the poor selectivity of NCDs to Fe3+ and important role of buffer solution. Additionally, under the same pH 7.4 condition, the QE of Fe3+ in NaH2PO4-Na2HPO4 system was sharply decreased to 47.6%, which may be caused by the reduction of iron concentration due to the formation of white phosphate precipitation (as shown in 
                              Fig. S15
                           ). The above results indicate that buffer solutions have a significant impact on QE and selectivity of Fe3+, the excellent selectivity of NCDs to Fe3+ in the tris-HCl system benefits from the formation of ferric hydroxide colloid. Surprisingly, Hg2+ displayed an extremely high QE (96.5%) in the NaH2PO4-Na2HPO4 buffer system, which needs further study.
